data.content:
In xUnit, setup/teardown maps to constructor/dispose and `IClassFixture<T>`:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture class |

Here's your converted class:

```csharp
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        // Per-test setup (replaces [SetUp])
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        // Per-test teardown (replaces [TearDown])
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **Constructor** runs before each test (replaces `[SetUp]`)
- **`IDisposable.Dispose()`** runs after each test (replaces `[TearDown]`)
- **`IClassFixture<T>`** creates the fixture once per class and injects it via constructor (replaces `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`)
- xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so the constructor/dispose pattern works naturally
- If you need to share the fixture across multiple test classes, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with `[Collection("name")]` instead
